title: A Sound Synthesis Method Based on Characteristic of Closed Curves
title_en: A Sound Synthesis Method Based on Characteristic of Closed Curves
abstract: 本研究は閉曲線の特徴に基づく音響合成法を提案し、形状から直接時間信号と周波数成分を生成することで視覚情報と音響情報の結びつけを目指しています。提案手法は閉曲線点列を複素信号に変換して周波数フィルタや中点平均・FFTに基づく反復スムージングを適用し、時間方向の伸縮に対して特徴を保つ音を生成することを示しています。
abstract_en: This study proposes a sound synthesis method based on characteristics of closed curves that generates time-domain signals and frequency components directly from shapes to link visual and auditory information. The proposed method converts closed-curve point sequences to a complex signal and applies frequency-domain filtering and iterative mid-point averaging with FFT to produce sounds that preserve features under time-direction stretching.
positioning_summary: 本研究は閉曲線入力から得られる複素信号を用いて形状に由来する音を合成する問題を扱っていることを位置づけの中心にしています。位置づけとして本研究は閉曲線→音生成のギャップを埋めることを目的とし、パフォーマーやインタラクション設計者向けに時間歪みに対する不変性を重視している点を強調しています。
positioning_summary_en: This study positions itself as addressing the problem of synthesizing shape-derived sounds using complex signals obtained from closed-curve inputs. The study positions its aim as closing the gap in closed-curve-to-sound generation and emphasizes robustness to time distortions for performers and interaction designers.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は閉曲線由来の特徴を保持したまま時間方向の伸縮に不変な音響合成法を提供することです。目的の具体的内容として本研究は複素信号 z(t)=x(t)+i y(t) を用いて時間歪みに対する不変性を保ちながら形状から音を合成することを狙っていると述べています。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this study is to provide a sound synthesis method that preserves closed-curve-derived features while remaining invariant to time-direction stretching. The study specifically aims to use the complex signal z(t)=x(t)+i y(t) to synthesize sounds from shapes while maintaining invariance to temporal warping.
method_summary: 本研究の手法は閉曲線点列を複素信号 z(t)=x(t)+i y(t) に変換し、周波数領域で特定のフィルタを適用して実部 Re[e^{iθ}z(t)] を処理することでスペクトル |X(ω)| を得る点を中核としています。手法の具体的な処理として本研究は F(ω)=i (ω<0), 0 (ω=0), −i (ω>0) の周波数フィルタを用い、点列の中点平均とFFTに基づく反復スムージング（例: n=100 回）を導入して安定化を図っています。
method_summary_en: The method central to this study converts closed-curve point sequences into the complex signal z(t)=x(t)+i y(t) and processes the real part Re[e^{iθ}z(t)] with frequency-domain filtering to obtain the spectrum |X(ω)|. Specifically, the study applies the frequency filter F(ω)=i (ω<0), 0 (ω=0), −i (ω>0) and uses mid-point averaging with FFT-based iterative smoothing (e.g., n=100 iterations) to stabilize the closed-curve representation.
evaluation_summary: 本研究の評価は時間波形の可視化とFFTによる周波数スペクトル比較という信号処理上の手法で行われています。評価の結果として本研究は反復スムージング後の z100 と ˜z100 が近似して収束し、周波数スペクトルの類似が確認されたことを報告し、聴覚評価は行われていない点も明示しています。
evaluation_summary_en: The evaluation in this study was conducted using signal-processing methods consisting of time-domain waveform visualization and FFT-based frequency spectrum comparisons. The evaluation results reported that after iterative smoothing the sequences z100 and ˜z100 approximated and converged and that spectral similarity was confirmed, while no auditory listening tests were conducted.

Title: A Sound Synthesis Method Based on Characteristic of Closed Curves
Authors: Yuuki Iwabuchi, Junichi Akita, Akio Kitagawa
Year: 2008
Abstract: This study proposes a sound synthesis method based on characteristics of closed curves that generates time-domain signals and frequency components directly from shapes to link visual and auditory information. The proposed method converts closed-curve point sequences to a complex signal and applies frequency-domain filtering and iterative mid-point averaging with FFT to produce sounds that preserve features under time-direction stretching.
Positioning Summary: This study positions itself as addressing the problem of synthesizing shape-derived sounds using complex signals obtained from closed-curve inputs. The study positions its aim as closing the gap in closed-curve-to-sound generation and emphasizes robustness to time distortions for performers and interaction designers.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this study is to provide a sound synthesis method that preserves closed-curve-derived features while remaining invariant to time-direction stretching. The study specifically aims to use the complex signal z(t)=x(t)+i y(t) to synthesize sounds from shapes while maintaining invariance to temporal warping.
Method Summary: The method central to this study converts closed-curve point sequences into the complex signal z(t)=x(t)+i y(t) and processes the real part Re[e^{iθ}z(t)] with frequency-domain filtering to obtain the spectrum |X(ω)|. Specifically, the study applies the frequency filter F(ω)=i (ω<0), 0 (ω=0), −i (ω>0) and uses mid-point averaging with FFT-based iterative smoothing (e.g., n=100 iterations) to stabilize the closed-curve representation.
Evaluation Summary: The evaluation in this study was conducted using signal-processing methods consisting of time-domain waveform visualization and FFT-based frequency spectrum comparisons. The evaluation results reported that after iterative smoothing the sequences z100 and ˜z100 approximated and converged and that spectral similarity was confirmed, while no auditory listening tests were conducted.
